Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place @butter{2%tbsp} in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}; set aside to soften (you'll use it in the Old Bay toast step). Wash and dry produce.

Core, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1} into 1/4-inch pieces. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1/2-inch pieces. Drain and rinse @corn{1}.

Melt @plain butter{2%tbsp} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add green pepper and scallion whites; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @flour{1%tablespoon}; cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{1%minute}.

Slowly stir @milk{1} into pot a splash at a time until fully incorporated.

Stir in 1 1/2 cups water. Add potatoes, @veggie stock concentrate{2}, and half the @Old Bay seasoning{1%unit}. Bring to a boil and cook, stirring occasionally, until potatoes are very tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> To test, pierce one piece with a fork—it should go through easily.

Heat a #medium dry pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce}; cook, turning occasionally, until crispy, ~{6-10%minutes}. Transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Once cool enough to handle, roughly chop.

Meanwhile, combine softened butter, 1/4 tsp Old Bay seasoning, and 1/4 tsp @sugar{1/4%tsp} until smooth. (TIP: If the butter is still cold, microwave for ~{10%seconds} to soften.) Taste and add more Old Bay seasoning if desired.

Halve @demi-baguette{1} lengthwise; spread cut sides with Old Bay butter. Place cut sides up on a #baking sheet{}.

Toast on top rack until golden, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Once potatoes are tender, reduce heat to low and mash with a #potato masher{} or #fork{} to desired consistency.

> We recommend mashing until almost smooth, leaving a few small potato pieces for texture.

Stir in @cream cheese{2%tablespoon}, corn, and @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup} until fully incorporated and chowder is thick and creamy (it will be very thick at this point). If needed, stir in splashes of water until chowder reaches desired consistency. Season generously with salt and pepper.

After chowder reaches desired consistency, stir in bacon.

Halve Old Bay toast on a diagonal if desired.

Divide chowder between #bowls{}. Garnish with scallion greens and @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon}. Serve with Old Bay toast on the side.

> Bacon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.